ODE VII.

‘ Don't weep, Asterie, sor your absent Gyges. He will come back to

you with the spring and bring a wealth of Bithyniam merehandize. He ¹

It is all in vain that his hostess Chloe tries every art to win him, sends emissaries to tell him of her passion and to prove to him from mythology the folly of constancy; he turns a deas ear to it all.

As Orelli characterizes it, ‘ezsszzxmov mercatorum vitam amoresque lyrice describens? The names are Greek, the life Roman. Ritter points out the effect of this Ode in relieving by its lightness and grace the seriousness of the preceding six. Compare the position of Od. 1. 38.

Lines 1—8. The first stanza gives the reasons why she should not weep 'for him: ‘ He will come back with the west winds of spring with the merchandize for which he sailed, and he will come back true to you.' The second stanza justifies the first prophecy, ‘he is only detained by the weather'; and the second, ‘even now he is pining to be at home with you.'
